In[5]:
def assign_age_class(rings):
    if rings <= 7:
        return 1
    elif 8 <= rings <= 10:
        return 2
    elif 11 <= rings <= 15:
        return 3
    else:
        return 4

data['AgeClass'] = data['Rings'].apply(assign_age_class)

In[13]:
X = abalone_encoded[features]     # (same features as PCA step)
y = abalone_encoded["AgeClass"]
results = []
In[14]:
depths = [3, 5, 7, 9, None]
min_samples = [2, 5, 10]

experiment = 1
for depth in depths:
    for min_leaf in min_samples:
        for seed in range(5):  # 5 random splits
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
                X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=seed, stratify=y
            )

            clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
                criterion="gini",
                max_depth=depth,
                min_samples_leaf=min_leaf,
                random_state=seed
            )

            clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
            y_pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
            y_pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)

            acc_train = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
            acc_test = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
            f1_train = f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train, average="macro")
            f1_test = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test, average="macro")

            results.append({
                "Exp": experiment,
                "Depth": depth,
                "MinLeaf": min_leaf,
                "Seed": seed,
                "Train_Acc": acc_train,
                "Test_Acc": acc_test,
                "Train_F1": f1_train,
                "Test_F1": f1_test
            })
            experiment += 1

results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
print(" Completed Multiple Runs")
print(results_df.head())

# ==============================================================
# STEP 14: Pruning Investigation  Cost-Complexity Post-Pruning
# ==============================================================

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier, plot_tree
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 1: Split again (same as before to stay consistent)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 2: Get cost-complexity pruning path ( values)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
path = best_clf.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities
print(f"Number of candidate  values: {len(ccp_alphas)}")

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 3: Train models for each  and record performance
# --------------------------------------------------------------
train_acc, test_acc, train_f1, test_f1 = [], [], [], []

for alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
        criterion="gini",
        random_state=42,
        ccp_alpha=alpha,
        max_depth=best_depth,
        min_samples_leaf=best_minleaf
    )
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    y_tr, y_te = clf.predict(X_train), clf.predict(X_test)

    train_acc.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_tr))
    test_acc.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_te))
    train_f1.append(f1_score(y_train, y_tr, average="macro"))
    test_f1.append(f1_score(y_test, y_te, average="macro"))

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 4: Plot  vs Accuracy / F1
# --------------------------------------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, test_acc, marker='o', label='Test Accuracy')
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, test_f1, marker='x', label='Test Macro-F1')
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, train_acc, linestyle='--', color='gray', label='Train Accuracy')
plt.xlabel("ccp_alpha (Pruning Strength)")
plt.ylabel("Performance")
plt.title("Cost-Complexity Pruning Curve")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("pruning_ccpalpha_curve.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 5: Select best  (max test F1)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
best_index = np.argmax(test_f1)
best_alpha = ccp_alphas[best_index]
print(f" Best  (max test F1): {best_alpha:.6f}")

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 6: Retrain pruned tree using best 
# --------------------------------------------------------------
pruned_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    criterion="gini",
    random_state=42,
    ccp_alpha=best_alpha,
    max_depth=best_depth,
    min_samples_leaf=best_minleaf
)
pruned_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 7: Evaluate pruned tree
# --------------------------------------------------------------
y_pred_pruned = pruned_tree.predict(X_test)
acc_pruned = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_pruned)
f1_pruned = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_pruned, average="macro")

print("\n Comparison of Original vs Pruned Tree:")
print(f"Original Tree Nodes : {best_clf.tree_.node_count}")
print(f"Pruned Tree Nodes   : {pruned_tree.tree_.node_count}")
print(f"Original Test Acc    : {accuracy_score(y_test, best_clf.predict(X_test)):.3f}")
print(f"Pruned Test Acc      : {acc_pruned:.3f}")
print(f"Original Macro-F1    : {f1_score(y_test, best_clf.predict(X_test), average='macro'):.3f}")
print(f"Pruned Macro-F1      : {f1_pruned:.3f}")

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 8: Visualise pruned tree (top 3 levels for report)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plot_tree(
    pruned_tree,
    feature_names=features,
    class_names=["Class1", "Class2", "Class3", "Class4"],
    filled=True,
    rounded=True,
    fontsize=9,
    max_depth=3
)
plt.title(f"Pruned Decision Tree (={best_alpha:.4f}, Top 3 Levels)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("abalone_pruned_tree_top3levels.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# ==============================================================
# STEP 15: Random Forest Investigation  Effect of Number of Trees
# ==============================================================

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import time

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 1: Define different numbers of trees to test
# --------------------------------------------------------------
n_trees = [10, 25, 50, 100, 200, 300]
results_rf = []

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 2: Loop over each number of trees
# --------------------------------------------------------------
for n in n_trees:
    start = time.time()

    rf = RandomForestClassifier(
        n_estimators=n,
        criterion="gini",
        max_depth=None,        # let trees grow fully (bagging helps reduce overfitting)
        min_samples_leaf=best_minleaf,
        random_state=42,
        n_jobs=-1              # use all CPU cores
    )
    rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    y_pred_train = rf.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = rf.predict(X_test)

    acc_train = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    acc_test = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    f1_train = f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train, average="macro")
    f1_test = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test, average="macro")

    elapsed = time.time() - start

    results_rf.append({
        "n_estimators": n,
        "Train_Acc": acc_train,
        "Test_Acc": acc_test,
        "Train_F1": f1_train,
        "Test_F1": f1_test,
        "FitTime": round(elapsed, 2)
    })

rf_df = pd.DataFrame(results_rf)
print("\n Random Forest Results Summary:")
print(rf_df)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 3: Plot number of trees vs performance
# --------------------------------------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
plt.plot(rf_df["n_estimators"], rf_df["Test_Acc"], marker='o', label="Test Accuracy")
plt.plot(rf_df["n_estimators"], rf_df["Train_Acc"], linestyle='--', color='gray', label="Train Accuracy")
plt.xlabel("Number of Trees (n_estimators)")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.title("Random Forest Performance vs Number of Trees")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("rf_accuracy_vs_trees.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
plt.plot(rf_df["n_estimators"], rf_df["Test_F1"], marker='o', label="Test Macro-F1", color='purple')
plt.xlabel("Number of Trees (n_estimators)")
plt.ylabel("Macro-F1 Score")
plt.title("Random Forest Macro-F1 vs Number of Trees")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("rf_f1_vs_trees.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 4: Identify the best performing Random Forest
# --------------------------------------------------------------
best_rf_row = rf_df.sort_values(by="Test_F1", ascending=False).iloc[0]
best_n = best_rf_row["n_estimators"]
best_rf = RandomForestClassifier(
    n_estimators=int(best_n),
    criterion="gini",
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1
).fit(X_train, y_train)

print(f"\n Best Random Forest uses n_estimators={best_n}")
print(f"Test Accuracy = {best_rf_row['Test_Acc']:.3f}, Macro-F1 = {best_rf_row['Test_F1']:.3f}")

# STEP 16 (FIXED): Gradient Boosting and XGBoost / HistGB Comparison
# ==============================================================

from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier, HistGradientBoostingClassifier, RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import time

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 0  Ensure labels start at 0  (fix for XGBoost / HistGB)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(y)   # Converts [1,2,3,4]  [0,1,2,3]

# Recreate train/test split to keep labels consistent
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 1  Try importing XGBoost, otherwise use HistGB
# --------------------------------------------------------------

    from xgboost import XGBClassifier
    XGB_AVAILABLE = True
    print(" Using XGBoost library.")

    print(" XGBoost not available, falling back to HistGradientBoostingClassifier.")
    XGB_AVAILABLE = False

# Step 2  Initialise ensemble models

models = {
    "RandomForest": RandomForestClassifier(
        n_estimators=int(best_n),
        criterion="gini",
        random_state=42,
        n_jobs=-1
    ),
    "GradientBoosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(
        n_estimators=200,
        learning_rate=0.1,
        max_depth=3,
        random_state=42
    )
}

if XGB_AVAILABLE:
    models["XGBoost"] = XGBClassifier(
        n_estimators=200,
        learning_rate=0.1,
        max_depth=3,
        subsample=0.8,
        colsample_bytree=0.8,
        random_state=42,
        n_jobs=-1,
        eval_metric="mlogloss",
        use_label_encoder=False
    )
else:
    models["HistGradientBoosting"] = HistGradientBoostingClassifier(
        max_iter=200,
        learning_rate=0.1,
        max_depth=3,
        random_state=42
    )

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 3  Train, evaluate, record
# --------------------------------------------------------------
results_gb = []

for name, model in models.items():
    start = time.time()
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average="macro")
    elapsed = time.time() - start

    results_gb.append({
        "Model": name,
        "Test_Accuracy": acc,
        "Test_MacroF1": f1,
        "Train_Time(s)": round(elapsed, 2)

# ==============================================================
# STEP 17: PCA (95% and 98% variance) with Best Ensemble Model
# ==============================================================

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import time

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 1  Standardise features before PCA
# --------------------------------------------------------------
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)    # scale all features for PCA

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 2  Fit PCA once and inspect cumulative variance
# --------------------------------------------------------------
pca_full = PCA().fit(X_scaled)
cumulative_var = np.cumsum(pca_full.explained_variance_ratio_) * 100

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_var)+1), cumulative_var, marker='o')
plt.axhline(y=95, color='r', linestyle='--', label='95% variance')
plt.axhline(y=98, color='g', linestyle='--', label='98% variance')
plt.xlabel("Number of Components")
plt.ylabel("Cumulative Variance Explained (%)")
plt.title("PCA Cumulative Variance Curve")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("pca_variance_curve.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# Find the number of components for 95% and 98% variance
n_comp_95 = np.argmax(cumulative_var >= 95) + 1
n_comp_98 = np.argmax(cumulative_var >= 98) + 1
print(f"Components for 95% variance: {n_comp_95}")
print(f"Components for 98% variance: {n_comp_98}")

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 3  Transform data using 95% and 98% components
# --------------------------------------------------------------
pca_95 = PCA(n_components=n_comp_95)
X_pca95 = pca_95.fit_transform(X_scaled)

pca_98 = PCA(n_components=n_comp_98)
X_pca98 = pca_98.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# Recreate splits for each version
X_train95, X_test95, y_train95, y_test95 = train_test_split(
    X_pca95, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)
X_train98, X_test98, y_train98, y_test98 = train_test_split(
    X_pca98, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 4  Train best model on full, 95%, and 98% PCA data
# --------------------------------------------------------------
from xgboost import XGBClassifier

models_pca = {
    "Full (No PCA)": XGBClassifier(
        n_estimators=200, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3,
        subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.8, random_state=42,
        n_jobs=-1, eval_metric="mlogloss", use_label_encoder=False
    ),
    "PCA 95%": XGBClassifier(
        n_estimators=200, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3,
        subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.8, random_state=42,
        n_jobs=-1, eval_metric="mlogloss", use_label_encoder=False
    ),
    "PCA 98%": XGBClassifier(
        n_estimators=200, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3,
        subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.8, random_state=42,
        n_jobs=-1, eval_metric="mlogloss", use_label_encoder=False
    )
}

results_pca = []
splits = {
    "Full (No PCA)": (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test),
    "PCA 95%": (X_train95, X_test95, y_train95, y_test95),
    "PCA 98%": (X_train98, X_test98, y_train98, y_test98),
}

for name, model in models_pca.items():
    Xt, Xv, yt, yv = splits[name]
    start = time.time()
    model.fit(Xt, yt)
    y_pred = model.predict(Xv)
    elapsed = round(time.time() - start, 2)

    acc = accuracy_score(yv, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(yv, y_pred, average="macro")

    results_pca.append({
        "Version": name,
        "Accuracy": acc,
        "Macro-F1": f1,
        "Train_Time(s)": elapsed
    })

pca_results_df = pd.DataFrame(results_pca)
print("\n PCA Comparison Results:")
print(pca_results_df)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 5  Plot comparison
# --------------------------------------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
plt.bar(pca_results_df["Version"], pca_results_df["Macro-F1"], color=["teal", "orange", "gold"])
plt.title("Effect of PCA on XGBoost Performance")
plt.ylabel("Macro-F1")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("pca_xgboost_comparison.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# STEP 18: Simple Neural Network (MLP)  Adam vs SGD Comparison
# ==============================================================

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import time

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 1  Prepare scaled data (NNs need normalised features)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler_nn = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler_nn.fit_transform(X)

X_train_nn, X_test_nn, y_train_nn, y_test_nn = train_test_split(
    X_scaled, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 2  Define and train models (Adam vs SGD)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
models_nn = {
    "MLP_Adam": MLPClassifier(
        hidden_layer_sizes=(64, 32), activation='relu',
        solver='adam', max_iter=300, random_state=42
    ),
    "MLP_SGD": MLPClassifier(
        hidden_layer_sizes=(64, 32), activation='relu',
        solver='sgd', learning_rate_init=0.01,
        max_iter=500, random_state=42
    )
}

results_nn = []

for name, model in models_nn.items():
    start = time.time()
    model.fit(X_train_nn, y_train_nn)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_nn)
    elapsed = round(time.time() - start, 2)

    acc = accuracy_score(y_test_nn, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test_nn, y_pred, average="macro")

    results_nn.append({
        "Model": name,
        "Accuracy": acc,
        "Macro-F1": f1,
        "Train_Time(s)": elapsed
    })

nn_results_df = pd.DataFrame(results_nn)
print("\n Neural Network (Adam vs SGD) Results:")
print(nn_results_df)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 3  Plot comparison
# --------------------------------------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
plt.bar(nn_results_df["Model"], nn_results_df["Macro-F1"], color=["royalblue", "darkorange"])
plt.title("Simple Neural Network Comparison  Adam vs SGD")
plt.ylabel("Macro-F1")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("mlp_adam_vs_sgd.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# ==============================================================
# STEP 19: MLP with Adam  L2 Regularisation () and Dropout
# ==============================================================

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, f1_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import time
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 1  Preprocess (scale features again)
# --------------------------------------------------------------
scaler_reg = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler_reg.fit_transform(X)

X_train_reg, X_test_reg, y_train_reg, y_test_reg = train_test_split(
    X_scaled, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 2  Define combinations of  (L2) and dropout rates
# --------------------------------------------------------------
# These are small () and moderate dropout values suitable for tabular data
combinations = [
    {"alpha": 1e-5, "dropout": 0.0},
    {"alpha": 1e-4, "dropout": 0.2},
    {"alpha": 1e-3, "dropout": 0.5}
]

results_reg = []

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 3  Train models for each combination
# --------------------------------------------------------------
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.optim as optim
from torch.utils.data import TensorDataset, DataLoader

# Convert data to PyTorch tensors
X_train_t = torch.tensor(X_train_reg, dtype=torch.float32)
y_train_t = torch.tensor(y_train_reg, dtype=torch.long)
X_test_t = torch.tensor(X_test_reg, dtype=torch.float32)
y_test_t = torch.tensor(y_test_reg, dtype=torch.long)

def train_torch_mlp(alpha, dropout_rate, epochs=60, lr=0.001, batch_size=64):
    input_dim = X_train_t.shape[1]
    hidden1, hidden2 = 64, 32
    output_dim = len(np.unique(y))

    model = nn.Sequential(
        nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden1),
        nn.ReLU(),
        nn.Dropout(dropout_rate),
        nn.Linear(hidden1, hidden2),
        nn.ReLU(),
        nn.Dropout(dropout_rate),
        nn.Linear(hidden2, output_dim)
    )

    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
    optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=lr, weight_decay=alpha)

    dataset = TensorDataset(X_train_t, y_train_t)
    loader = DataLoader(dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)

    for epoch in range(epochs):
        model.train()
        for Xb, yb in loader:
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            preds = model(Xb)
            loss = criterion(preds, yb)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()

    # Evaluate
    model.eval()
    with torch.no_grad():
        preds = model(X_test_t).argmax(dim=1)
        acc = accuracy_score(y_test_reg, preds)
        f1 = f1_score(y_test_reg, preds, average="macro")

    return acc, f1

# Run experiments
for combo in combinations:
    start = time.time()
    acc, f1 = train_torch_mlp(combo["alpha"], combo["dropout"])
    elapsed = round(time.time() - start, 2)

    results_reg.append({
        "L2 ()": combo["alpha"],
        "Dropout": combo["dropout"],
        "Accuracy": acc,
        "Macro-F1": f1,
        "Train_Time(s)": elapsed
    })

results_reg_df = pd.DataFrame(results_reg)
print("\n Adam Regularisation Results (L2 + Dropout):")
print(results_reg_df)

# --------------------------------------------------------------
# Step 4  Plot Macro-F1 vs combination
# --------------------------------------------------------------
labels = [f"={row['L2 ()']}, Dropout={row['Dropout']}" for _, row in results_reg_df.iterrows()]

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.bar(labels, results_reg_df["Macro-F1"], color=["royalblue","orange","red"])
plt.ylabel("Macro-F1 Score")
plt.title("Adam Regularisation: Effect of L2 Weight Decay and Dropout")
plt.xticks(rotation=30, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("adam_regularisation_comparison.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()
